<subsection xml:id="subsec-conversion-of-fractions-to-decimals">
    <title>Conversion of fractions to decimals</title>
    <p> 
        To convert a fraction into a decimal, we divide the numerator by the denominator. 
        For instance, to find the decimal equivalent of a fraction such as <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>,
        divide <m>1</m> by <m>2</m>, which gives <m>1 \div 2 = 0.5</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Alternatively, we can convert a fraction to a decimal by writing its equivalence 
        fraction with a denominator which is divisible by <m>10.</m>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Identify a number that, when multiplied by the denominator, results in 
                    <m>10, 100, 1000,</m> or any number that is <m>1</m> followed by zeros.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Multiply both the numerator and the denominator by that number to create an 
                    equivalent fraction with a denominator that is a power of <m>10</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Write down the numerator of the new fraction. 
                    Move the decimal point to the left by as many places as there are zeros in the denominator.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
